1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:26,000
 Ben, let me just give you one last example in terms of my experience, and I won't name names because the students will get mad at me, but I asked them at the beginning of the semester how many of them, and I probably should have waited so that they have confidence in me and whatnot, but how many of you have AI girlfriends or AI boyfriends? And they all kind of snickered, they all kind of chuckled, ah, you know, and nobody raised their hand.

2
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:49,000
 And then later, in office hours, I found that when they were alone with me, they said I spent roughly two to three hours a day chatting with an AI, usually at night time. And they think, at the beginning, they think it's a cure for loneliness, but as time goes on, they realize it's not.

3
00:00:49,000 --> 00:01:16,000
 Fr. Philip, Matthew, it's wonderful to have this ability to have a conversation with both of you here in studio in Rome. And so Matthew, I'd like to begin with you. There is so much change going on right now in AI. It feels like every single day, there's a new update, there's a new technological innovation that is blowing our minds, that's breaking all the previously expected records, or, you know,

4
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:38,000
 our capabilities of where we would think we'd be in now. Now, if we look forward, and this might be impossible, but that's why I want to ask it. If we look forward in 10 years, you know, what, hypothetically, at least, what could our relationship to technology be like? What could our relationship to AI be like? What, you know, what our everyday, you know, life look like?

5
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:53,280
 Well, I think to answer that question, you'd have to kind of consider which way we're currently breaking, right? Are we on the good path, or the super abundance path that Eon likes to talk about? Or are we on kind of like the doomer path, right? Where it's all going to end?

6
00:01:53,280 --> 00:02:10,060
 I don't think we've definitively made any decisions right now that would kind of doom us to one or the other, necessarily. So, you know, I tend to think that there's still a really good opportunity here to ensure that, you know, we head on that golden path towards a very, you know, to a very brighter future.

7
00:02:10,420 --> 00:02:27,540
 But I think there's some very important decisions that we made in the next year that I think will have a huge influence on which way we break. Part of that is, I think, how much time and energy we're putting into mechanic interoperability, trying to understand the black box of these models so we can make sure that they're effectively aligned, right?

8
00:02:27,540 --> 00:02:40,160
 Because for the most part, I mean, we know it has set the conditions for them to emerge, grow them, right? Because that's essentially what's happening, according to Anthropic. But we don't know how to steer them effectively, right?

9
00:02:40,220 --> 00:02:51,760
 I mean, aside from a very superficial level. And in the end of the day, I mean, whether they have been effectively steered or not is really just a question of observing their behavior, right? Because we can't observe their internal thought processes, we don't know for sure.

10
00:02:51,760 --> 00:03:10,020
 So, I think the ability to steer these models is going to have a significant impact on what life's going to be like in the future. So, let's just say things break in a positive direction. We figure out how to keep these models aligned to us, and they end up serving human flourishing. You know, I think it's

11
00:03:10,020 --> 00:03:25,140
 It's very likely that we'll have kind of two economies that will emerge, right? There's the more conventional GDP economy, which is, you know, building up technology and manufacturing. And I'm sure people like Elon will be trying to use that to get us to Mars.

12
00:03:26,600 --> 00:03:42,780
 And then you'll have this kind of, like we call like Etsy economy, right? Whereas it's people who now have time on their hands are choosing to, you know, use their gifts and abilities to kind of give that human touch back to good and services. And this economy will emerge with people who want to pay more for those goods and services because they're human.

13
00:03:43,160 --> 00:03:53,740
 So, I think that there'll still be lots of work to be done in the future. So, I think people will still be busy. I think it's likely that it'll be kind of a mass migration out of cities where people, you know, want to connect again with nature.

14
00:03:53,880 --> 00:04:07,540
 And they probably want to, you know, move into kind of tighter communities and work on building kind of friendships and having more time, right, to spend with their kids outdoors. The things that we typically dream about as human beings and often have to sacrifice, you know, in order to pay our mortgages.

15
00:04:07,540 --> 00:04:19,160
 So, I think that trajectory is probably inevitable if the technology breaks in the right direction. If it doesn't break, you know, in the right direction, you know, there's a lot of science fiction movies which have kind of possibly how this would look.

16
00:04:19,160 --> 00:04:29,980
 But I do think you'd have kind of a massive welfare state, a lot of inequality. You'd have a lot of people addicted to VR and gaming and things like that. And I think you'd have a real high casualty rate.

17
00:04:29,980 --> 00:04:33,520
 I think a lot of people would be chasing dopamine hits, as I've said before, right off of a cliff.

18
00:04:34,360 --> 00:04:52,980
 So, in many ways, you know, we may have conquered disease, and provided AI doesn't kill us. We may have conquered disease. We may have access to, you know, unlimited information. But I think that ultimately, because our formation is poor, because the church's evangelization has failed, people are lost.

19
00:04:52,980 --> 00:05:02,780
 And Father, I know that you've, you know, you're a professor, you work with students. These are oftentimes some of the youngest, brightest of these upcoming generations.

20
00:05:03,460 --> 00:05:23,940
 When they come to you, and they look for spiritual wisdom, for hope, for kind of that formation, and looking into that next chapter, when they start to have a career, when they start to form families, when you look 10 years down the line, and you see maybe an 18-year-old who you, you know, you're starting to teach, they're asking the right questions, they're curious, they have all that enthusiasm.

21
00:05:24,460 --> 00:05:34,260
 What roadmap do you send them on? What does that look like when you start to prepare someone for a future that, arguably, we're speculating, we're thinking about, we're dreaming?

22
00:05:34,620 --> 00:05:44,240
 The students tell me that they're, first of all, they're not afraid of AI, which, which is kind of interesting. And this is the generation that grew up with AI.

23
00:05:44,240 --> 00:05:56,280
 Well, is growing up with AI, because I think what, like Matthew said, what we're going to see in the next five to 10 years is going to be pretty spectacular compared to what we see today.

24
00:05:57,280 --> 00:06:05,320
 They're not afraid of AI, and maybe because they haven't thought about the possibility of, you know, the human race being destroyed.

25
00:06:05,320 --> 00:06:12,660
 The second thing which is important to them is to understand how to use it to their advantage.

26
00:06:12,660 --> 00:06:23,200
 So let me put it this way. They're not so much afraid of the AI as they are of not using it in the right way.

27
00:06:23,200 --> 00:06:35,760
 In other words, their competition is not against the AI, but against somebody who has dominated the AI and is competing for the same position, the same job, the same space in society.

28
00:06:35,760 --> 00:06:38,520
 And so I thought that that was fascinating.

29
00:06:38,520 --> 00:06:47,760
 Jeffrey Hinton, who is the godfather of AI, they say, and he won the Nobel Prize in physics for machine learning.

30
00:06:47,760 --> 00:06:53,200
 He's one of the pioneers of machine learning, has a recent interview, and you can find it on YouTube.

31
00:06:53,200 --> 00:06:54,140
 It's quite popular.

32
00:06:54,140 --> 00:07:00,040
 And the title is, These Jobs Will No Longer Be Around in 20 Months.

33
00:07:00,040 --> 00:07:02,380
 You may have seen it.

34
00:07:02,380 --> 00:07:03,540
 It's quite popular.

35
00:07:03,540 --> 00:07:07,420
 And so things are really going to change.

36
00:07:07,420 --> 00:07:08,860
 Things are really going to change.

37
00:07:08,860 --> 00:07:28,420
 What I foresee is we're going to adapt and we're going to be used to living with AIs, AIs as part of society that you're going to have to live with and you're going to have to take into account, which today is not that common.

38
00:07:28,420 --> 00:07:33,400
 We don't relate to an AI as if it were an entity.

39
00:07:33,400 --> 00:07:48,100
 We kind of, especially if you're still using queries at typing them in and instead of using your voice and looking at a video or an audio, which is much more humane, that's the way we deal with each other.

40
00:07:48,100 --> 00:07:53,100
 And so I think the platforms are becoming more and more humane in that sense.

41
00:07:53,100 --> 00:07:54,140
 They're becoming easier.

42
00:07:54,140 --> 00:07:57,460
 The interfaces are becoming more and more human-like.

43
00:07:57,460 --> 00:08:00,000
 And so that makes it easier to use.

44
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:11,460
 Once the human race understands the presence of AIs as part of our society, a lot's going to change.

45
00:08:11,460 --> 00:08:13,320
 But I think we're just going to get used to it.

46
00:08:13,520 --> 00:08:18,380
 How comfortable would you be if the robots in the future looked like us when we're walking around?

47
00:08:18,380 --> 00:08:20,480
 Not at all.

48
00:08:20,480 --> 00:08:29,480
 And Stanford made a great study, psychological study, because they showcased some of the first robots, Stanford University.

49
00:08:29,480 --> 00:08:34,480
 And at the beginning, there were basically two moods, two things.

50
00:08:34,480 --> 00:08:40,700
 At the beginning, there was a sense of excitement and novelty because they would send the robots out on campus, right?

51
00:08:40,700 --> 00:08:43,420
 Oh, and people would turn and they'd think that was great.

52
00:08:43,520 --> 00:08:50,680
 As time went on, like two or three months in, they started destroying the robots because the humans felt threatened.

53
00:08:50,680 --> 00:08:58,780
 And so you have students with bats going out, baseball bats, going out and actually, you know, ruining the robots.

54
00:08:58,780 --> 00:09:03,020
 You have people that would cross the street to avoid being on the same.

55
00:09:03,020 --> 00:09:04,000
 Yeah, yeah.

56
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:08,820
 But these are like the unitary robots that like they aren't, I mean, they are humanoid.

57
00:09:08,820 --> 00:09:09,680
 Right, right, right.

58
00:09:09,680 --> 00:09:12,200
 But imagine they look like us.

59
00:09:12,200 --> 00:09:12,960
 Do you still think?

60
00:09:12,960 --> 00:09:14,740
 I think it would be even worse.

61
00:09:14,740 --> 00:09:17,820
 If you can tell that it's not human.

62
00:09:17,820 --> 00:09:18,280
 Right, right.

63
00:09:18,280 --> 00:09:19,840
 Yeah, it's going to be even scarier.

64
00:09:19,840 --> 00:09:23,720
 That's like the Westworld scenario is something that I think a lot about, right?

65
00:09:23,720 --> 00:09:34,260
 I mean, at some point, are we going to have to say, if robots are really living, you know, day-to-day lives with robots and making them walking by us in the street, they have to have some kind of, there has to be some clear indication that this is a robot.

66
00:09:34,480 --> 00:09:43,580
 I mean, I do kind of feel that that may be something that we need to do just for the health of civilization, right?

67
00:09:43,580 --> 00:09:47,260
 Because I think that the dynamics between people and robots could get very unhealthy.

68
00:09:47,260 --> 00:09:50,700
 I mean, obviously, we're already seeing crazy projection, right?

69
00:09:50,820 --> 00:09:51,820
 Like, think of character, I act.

70
00:09:51,820 --> 00:09:54,180
 That's something that worries me.

71
00:09:54,180 --> 00:09:55,540
 Matthew, if you can unpack that.

72
00:09:55,800 --> 00:10:04,580
 So, for a lot of people who aren't, you know, focusing on this on a daily basis, the idea of robots, you know, literally interacting with humans on a daily basis seems something, you know, from science fiction.

73
00:10:04,580 --> 00:10:06,080
 How likely is that?

74
00:10:06,080 --> 00:10:15,060
 And how soon do you foresee, you know, robots being on, maybe not on the streets of Rome, but definitely, you know, on the streets of, you know, in Mountain View, in Silicon Valley, and some of these.

75
00:10:15,060 --> 00:10:16,520
 Well, they're already in the factories, right?

76
00:10:16,520 --> 00:10:17,920
 I mean, we're already starting to see them deployed.

77
00:10:17,920 --> 00:10:21,020
 I mean, figure robots are on the BMW manufacturing floor, right?

78
00:10:21,020 --> 00:10:22,500
 And Amazon's deploying them like crazy.

79
00:10:22,660 --> 00:10:27,200
 So, I think, you know, I think for some time, to some extent, we've been interacting with robots.

80
00:10:27,200 --> 00:10:32,580
 But, you know, I think what's going to be wild is these robots, the form factors of the robots were very inhuman, right?

81
00:10:32,580 --> 00:10:35,020
 They weren't very intelligent, and they were in very specific lanes.

82
00:10:35,020 --> 00:10:41,300
 But now, I think as the robots become more generally intelligent and more humanoid, they're going to be able to move in kind of the human environment, right?

83
00:10:41,300 --> 00:10:44,440
 And so, that's the thing that gets very odd, right?

84
00:10:44,440 --> 00:10:47,720
 I mean, I think right now, I think manufacturing robots is very hard.

85
00:10:47,720 --> 00:10:50,480
 Only a few companies can do it, and we're still at the very, you know, early stages of this.

86
00:10:50,500 --> 00:10:53,360
 But if you're going to, like, fast forward 10 years, right?

87
00:10:53,360 --> 00:10:58,020
 At that point, we probably will have conquered the whole manufacturing complexity where we're shipping these things at scale.

88
00:10:58,020 --> 00:11:01,180
 I mean, Elon Musk thinks it'll be like, what, like 6 billion robots?

89
00:11:01,180 --> 00:11:03,960
 It's like, or more, you know, that he thinks they're-

90
00:11:03,960 --> 00:11:04,620
 He wants one in it.

91
00:11:04,620 --> 00:11:05,520
 Right.

92
00:11:05,520 --> 00:11:12,580
 And, you know, I think he said at times that there could be, you know, like some X factor more than there are humans on Earth, right?

93
00:11:12,580 --> 00:11:19,960
 So, and to some extent, I mean, I could see that being good, you know, if they're performing all the tasks that humans would prefer not to do.

94
00:11:19,960 --> 00:11:23,080
 And we have time for the things that we consider in life that really matter.

95
00:11:23,080 --> 00:11:30,440
 But I do worry about, like, I think when we think about, like, robots being manufactured at scale and being deployed in the world, we think about them just solving new world problems.

96
00:11:30,440 --> 00:11:36,200
 But we, like, sometimes we don't focus on how some people are going to, like, project and anthropomorphize those robots.

97
00:11:36,200 --> 00:11:45,660
 And because they haven't learned how to develop deep social connections, right, with others, that they may become attached to these things emotionally.

98
00:11:45,660 --> 00:11:50,580
 And so, like, I think it's quite possible some people when they say, you know, I love my robot and I'm going to marry my robot.

99
00:11:50,580 --> 00:11:56,320
 And everyone else in society, you have to accept that this is now my spouse and I expect it to be treated as such.

100
00:11:56,320 --> 00:12:03,820
 When I get invited to a party, I expect my robot wife to be there and my robot wife may look, you know, humanoid and I expect you to treat it like any other human.

101
00:12:03,820 --> 00:12:07,380
 Like, this is the kind of, like, these kind of, like, tensions, I think, are going to emerge.

102
00:12:07,380 --> 00:12:11,440
 And I don't think we as a society are ready for this yet, but I think it's probably inevitable.

103
00:12:11,440 --> 00:12:14,600
 Well, that just scared me, what you just said.

104
00:12:14,600 --> 00:12:16,440
 I hadn't really thought about that.

105
00:12:16,440 --> 00:12:25,540
 But I was in San Francisco about a month ago and Waymo has a bunch of self-driving taxis.

106
00:12:25,540 --> 00:12:29,300
 And, in fact, they're probably, I think, more now than the regular taxis.

107
00:12:29,300 --> 00:12:36,140
 But I remember watching a person hail a taxi and it was a person driving.

108
00:12:36,140 --> 00:12:37,400
 And they passed.

109
00:12:37,400 --> 00:12:38,900
 They said, no, no, keep going.

110
00:12:38,900 --> 00:12:40,660
 And they, because they wanted a Waymo.

111
00:12:40,660 --> 00:12:49,120
 And I thought, ooh, we're now preferring the self-driving car to the human driving car.

112
00:12:49,540 --> 00:12:54,120
 And there are a series, I looked this up, and I think there's a couple of reasons.

113
00:12:54,120 --> 00:12:59,900
 One, people tend to feel more relaxed without a human there.

114
00:12:59,900 --> 00:13:02,040
 They don't have to say anything if they don't want to.

115
00:13:02,040 --> 00:13:04,400
 They don't have to listen to anything if they don't want to.

116
00:13:04,800 --> 00:13:09,700
 But with a human, it's unpredictable.

117
00:13:09,700 --> 00:13:16,200
 You never know, you know, especially if they don't speak English very well, which is very common in San Francisco.

118
00:13:17,340 --> 00:13:18,880
 Better to learn Spanish.

119
00:13:18,880 --> 00:13:22,360
 But I think they're also safer.

120
00:13:22,360 --> 00:13:32,100
 I think if you look at the record, they have almost no crashes or no one has ever died yet.

121
00:13:32,220 --> 00:13:35,300
 Well, in a Tesla, one person did die about four years ago.

122
00:13:35,300 --> 00:13:37,340
 But Elon handled that, I think, well.

123
00:13:37,340 --> 00:13:39,320
 They made a mistake.

124
00:13:39,320 --> 00:13:48,520
 Anyway, the self-driving cars are statistically much safer than human driving cars.

125
00:13:48,520 --> 00:13:50,500
 You don't have to tip a robot either, right?

126
00:13:50,500 --> 00:13:51,580
 Presumably, right?

127
00:13:51,580 --> 00:13:55,320
 I mean, that's, I hear that complaint a lot about tipping culture, how it's, you know.

128
00:13:55,320 --> 00:13:57,320
 I mean, I mean.

129
00:13:57,320 --> 00:13:59,740
 That's another advantage, sure.

130
00:14:00,120 --> 00:14:02,820
 Yeah, I tend to agree.

131
00:14:02,820 --> 00:14:12,200
 I mean, I think if people have the choice, I think in the very near term, between interacting with a smart AI, not a dumb AI we dealt with when we called, you know, telephone lines in the past.

132
00:14:12,200 --> 00:14:20,780
 But a smart AI who can efficiently, you know, do what we need to do agentically or dealing with the human.

133
00:14:20,780 --> 00:14:25,320
 That's what's kind of crazy to me is I think most people are going to choose the AI, right?

134
00:14:25,400 --> 00:14:32,580
 And if you think about that, that puts a lot of pressure on companies to adapt, right, to people's new preferences.

135
00:14:32,580 --> 00:14:38,060
 And they will, right, because I think it saves them money and they're responding, you know, to what their customers want.

136
00:14:38,060 --> 00:14:42,560
 And so, you know, for those who are trying to, like, you know, keep people in the labor market, I think they have a real challenge.

137
00:14:43,100 --> 00:14:47,940
 Yeah, Ben, let me just give you one last example in terms of my experience.

138
00:14:47,940 --> 00:14:51,160
 And I won't name names because the students will get mad at me.

139
00:14:51,160 --> 00:14:58,980
 But I asked them at the beginning of the semester how many of them, and I probably should have waited so that they have confidence in me and whatnot.

140
00:14:58,980 --> 00:15:02,180
 But how many of you have AI girlfriends or AI boyfriends?

141
00:15:02,180 --> 00:15:03,800
 And they all kind of snickered.

142
00:15:03,800 --> 00:15:05,760
 They all kind of chuckled, you know.

143
00:15:06,700 --> 00:15:08,240
 And nobody raised their hand.

144
00:15:08,240 --> 00:15:22,220
 Later, in office hours, I found that when they were alone with me, they said I spent roughly two to three hours a day chatting with an AI, usually at nighttime.

145
00:15:23,580 --> 00:15:27,720
 And they think, at the beginning, they think it's a cure for loneliness.

146
00:15:27,720 --> 00:15:31,580
 But as time goes on, they realize it's not.

147
00:15:31,580 --> 00:15:37,480
 And Harvard just came out with a study about, Ron Ivey is actually doing a lot of work on this.

148
00:15:37,480 --> 00:15:40,960
 Like you mentioned, Character AI.

149
00:15:40,960 --> 00:15:45,440
 There are a lot of other platforms that are catering to emotional attachments.

150
00:15:45,440 --> 00:15:50,520
 And Harvard is finding empirical evidence that it does not cure loneliness.

151
00:15:50,920 --> 00:15:55,860
 You would think it would because you're interacting with the AI and it's responding.

152
00:15:55,860 --> 00:16:05,240
 If you ever saw the movie Her, you know, that's – but in reality, people understand that it's a one-way relationship.

153
00:16:05,240 --> 00:16:07,780
 On the other side, there's not a real human being.

154
00:16:07,780 --> 00:16:14,960
 And so, Father, if we play that forward and we keep this exercise of looking 10 years down the line, if we try to map that out.

155
00:16:14,960 --> 00:16:19,020
 And as Matthew mentioned, we have this fork and things can go, you know, very well.

156
00:16:19,020 --> 00:16:20,900
 And that's what we hope for and that's what we're working towards.

157
00:16:20,900 --> 00:16:23,680
 But things can also, you know, start to go in the wrong direction.

158
00:16:23,680 --> 00:16:32,180
 What do you think needs to happen now as we're kind of in that, you know, that genesis point where, you know, these companies are starting to develop these, you know, character AI.

159
00:16:32,260 --> 00:16:33,960
 And it's something that's still relatively new.

160
00:16:33,960 --> 00:16:44,980
 But if you have enormous, you know, percentages of the population and it's growing and they're lonely and they're using these AI, you know, chatbots to talk to, to confront their loneliness, to try to build relationships.

161
00:16:44,980 --> 00:16:46,760
 But it's obviously not solving that.

162
00:16:46,760 --> 00:16:48,720
 What needs to change now?

163
00:16:48,720 --> 00:16:52,960
 What can we do and what can the church do to address this issue?

164
00:16:52,960 --> 00:17:01,100
 One of the most important things is to realize how our purpose in life is tied to our jobs.

165
00:17:01,100 --> 00:17:05,480
 That, Matthew and I have spoken a lot about this.

166
00:17:05,480 --> 00:17:09,660
 In the future, that's not, that can't be the case because a lot of people aren't going to have a job.

167
00:17:09,660 --> 00:17:14,980
 They're not going to have a regular nine to five, you know, that, which is just simply part of reality.

168
00:17:14,980 --> 00:17:18,000
 And it has been for, you know, since Adam and Eve.

169
00:17:18,720 --> 00:17:29,540
 Father, if I can say something just on that, I think, and I totally agree with this, but I think that's a very hard reality that I don't really think people at all, honestly, are confronting because it's too existentially frightening.

170
00:17:29,540 --> 00:17:32,640
 The idea that enormous percentage of the population will not have a job.

171
00:17:32,640 --> 00:17:34,940
 Oh, you asked me what's going to happen in 10 years.

172
00:17:34,940 --> 00:17:42,180
 And that's one of, you know, if you talk to anybody, I just had a conversation yesterday with the head of AI for Salesforce, which is a large company.

173
00:17:42,180 --> 00:17:46,300
 And that was the first, he says, Father, what is the purpose of life?

174
00:17:46,760 --> 00:17:49,760
 And I'm like, John, I thought, John Defoe is his name.

175
00:17:49,760 --> 00:17:51,660
 He said, John, I thought we were going to talk about AI.

176
00:17:51,660 --> 00:17:53,960
 He says, oh, yeah, we're talking about AI.

177
00:17:53,960 --> 00:18:05,320
