 But I think if people don't have hope and we don't know, you know, again, to go back to Cardinal Collins, if we, if we don't know where we're going, we're not going to get there.

779
00:59:22,140 --> 00:59:22,500
 Right.

780
00:59:22,500 --> 00:59:24,240
 So, so it is important.

781
00:59:24,240 --> 00:59:36,660
 Like, like, I think it's important for we Catholics to talk about this issue and, and, and, and, and we, and we look to our, our Holy Father and we look to, we look to, you know, the teachings of, you know, the gospel and, and the saints and try and figure this out.

782
00:59:36,720 --> 00:59:42,600
 And I think in many ways, what we're going to find out is that, you know, the problems that we're dealing with are not new, that they're probably old ones, right?

783
00:59:42,600 --> 00:59:49,200
 That every civilization has probably struggled with, but we just have to kind of get back to first principles, you know, as far as our faith goes.

784
00:59:49,300 --> 00:59:58,280
 And just make sure that we're reorienting ourselves around those first principles and ensure that the civilizations that we're influencing around us are heading in this, are heading in that same direction.

785
00:59:58,280 --> 01:00:04,660
 I think there is a brilliant thinker who is actually taking up the, the issue, as you mentioned, that's Yuval Harari.

786
01:00:04,660 --> 01:00:18,820
 I hope I can mention, he has a new book I'm reading called Nexus, but the book that influenced me the most is called Homo Deus, where the final chapter is called Dedeism, where he warns us.

787
01:00:19,140 --> 01:00:23,040
 about the future of technology.

788
01:00:23,040 --> 01:00:26,380
 Now, if you, if you're familiar with his writing, he's very, very famous.

789
01:00:26,380 --> 01:00:29,540
 He is an historian in Israel.

790
01:00:29,540 --> 01:00:32,560
 I'm actually surprised that you brought him up because he is controversial.

791
01:00:32,560 --> 01:00:33,360
 That's interesting.

792
01:00:33,360 --> 01:00:34,000
 I don't agree.

793
01:00:34,000 --> 01:00:39,120
 And I tell, I teach his chapter in, in, in, in, in my course on technology.

794
01:00:39,120 --> 01:00:46,620
 I don't agree, but I don't, if you only teach stuff that you agree with, you're, you're very going to be very limited.

795
01:00:46,620 --> 01:00:53,720
 And so I remember telling my students, I said, yeah, I, I recommend Harari's books because I think he's a deep thinker.

796
01:00:53,720 --> 01:00:57,100
 And I said, oh yes, but he's, you know, very controversial.

797
01:00:57,100 --> 01:00:59,820
 And he said that, and I'm like, okay.

798
01:01:00,160 --> 01:01:13,400
 I didn't say I agree with everything he says, but one of the things, and I think to Matthew's point, I, I, I remember asking some people in Silicon Valley because he did a tour of Homo Deus a couple of years ago at Silicon Valley.

799
01:01:13,400 --> 01:01:16,580
 And he was, he was, uh, he's very popular with all the tech people.

800
01:01:16,580 --> 01:01:23,580
 And I said, um, you know, he, he, uh, what's he doing in the book?

801
01:01:23,580 --> 01:01:26,640
 Because he seems to be exalting the technology.

802
01:01:26,640 --> 01:01:28,860
 He says, no father, you haven't understood what he's doing.

803
01:01:28,860 --> 01:01:30,840
 What he's doing is warning us.

804
01:01:30,840 --> 01:01:36,000
 He's saying, uh, cause he doesn't agree with a techno, a techno society either.

805
01:01:36,000 --> 01:01:37,720
 He's very, very critical of that.

806
01:01:37,720 --> 01:01:40,560
 Uh, and, and so he's trying to jolt us.

807
01:01:40,560 --> 01:01:42,380
 He's, he's trying to shock us.

808
01:01:42,380 --> 01:01:51,620
 So the way he presents one of the, one of his famous phrases, uh, if, if you are looking for a mate, uh, Google is a lot better than a date.

809
01:01:51,620 --> 01:01:58,720
 You know, things, things like, cause he says the algorithm is going to get the better match for you than you just going on a date.

810
01:01:58,720 --> 01:02:00,900
 Now, well, it's going to edify your every impulse.

811
01:02:02,400 --> 01:02:14,200
 But I mean, those are the kinds of things and he disagrees with that, you know, he disagrees with that, but he writes in a way that you would, you would think, wait a second, are you suggesting that that's what we do?

812
01:02:14,200 --> 01:02:16,360
 He said, algorithms are going to beat humans.

813
01:02:16,360 --> 01:02:22,700
 No, but he's saying you got to wake up because this is the society that, that we're creating.

814
01:02:22,700 --> 01:02:23,920
 And I don't think we're alone in this.

815
01:02:23,920 --> 01:02:27,900
 I mean, I think there's, there's a lot of people out there who aren't Catholic, right.

816
01:02:27,900 --> 01:02:33,760
 Who would agree that the kind of the transhumanist vision of the future is not the one that we want to see play out here.

817
01:02:33,760 --> 01:02:33,960
 Right.

818
01:02:33,960 --> 01:02:38,560
 And I'm talking about like the cyber is going to be the one unless we take action.

819
01:02:38,560 --> 01:02:39,360
 Yeah, I agree.

820
01:02:39,360 --> 01:02:42,280
 I mean, like, like, you know, there's a video game that came out called Cyberpunk 2077.

821
01:02:42,280 --> 01:02:42,740
 Right.

822
01:02:42,740 --> 01:02:44,740
 And I was quite fascinated with this, with this game.

823
01:02:44,740 --> 01:02:51,340
 I just thought it was, it was, it was a great technical, uh, you know, achievement, but the future that it depicts were basically man and machine emerged.

824
01:02:51,340 --> 01:02:51,680
 Right.

825
01:02:51,680 --> 01:02:57,880
 And they're kind of stuck in this loop where they're, they're constantly trying to, you know, upgrade themselves and, and get a greater and greater capability.

826
01:02:57,880 --> 01:02:58,240
 Right.

827
01:02:58,240 --> 01:03:00,880
 And, and I think there's a real risk of that.

828
01:03:00,880 --> 01:03:01,120
 Right.

829
01:03:01,120 --> 01:03:04,180
 Especially in a society focused purely on utility, right.

830
01:03:04,180 --> 01:03:08,260
 Your value is based upon what you contribute to the GDP economy.

831
01:03:08,260 --> 01:03:08,560
 Right.

832
01:03:08,560 --> 01:03:11,040
 Or how much you contribute to a mission, like getting to Mars.

833
01:03:11,040 --> 01:03:20,300
 And, and so if, if that's like, that's what the, you know, your value is, then why wouldn't I, you know, insert some like neural link into my brain, expand my computational capability.

834
01:03:20,300 --> 01:03:21,300
 Right.

835
01:03:21,300 --> 01:03:27,180
 So I compete with, with, with AI's and machines and, and, and I, and I, and I, I feel like there'll be a lot of pressure for people to do that.

836
01:03:27,180 --> 01:03:36,540
 And I think that is a big threat because I think the minute we, we, we start heading down in this direction that man and machine need to merge, like that's our destiny.

837
01:03:36,540 --> 01:03:40,140
 I think, I think we're going to run off the rails real quick.

838
01:03:40,140 --> 01:03:41,760
 And I think that's almost a line.

839
01:03:41,760 --> 01:03:42,160
 Right.

840
01:03:42,160 --> 01:03:46,420
 And, and that isn't, that is an area that I hope that the church will weigh into directly.

841
01:03:46,420 --> 01:03:46,940
 Right.

842
01:03:46,940 --> 01:03:54,820
 And, and we, a while ago I had a conversation with Father Alejandro Crossweth, who's a professor at the Angelicum and he made a really good point.

843
01:03:54,820 --> 01:03:55,620
 It's not his point.

844
01:03:55,620 --> 01:03:59,100
 It's from the church, but he, he made it very eloquently, recounted it for us.

845
01:03:59,100 --> 01:04:06,300
 And he, and he said, you know, cause the question of, I was like, how far should this technology go?

846
01:04:06,700 --> 01:04:10,120
 You know, how far should like, like, like, like robotics go?

847
01:04:10,120 --> 01:04:18,460
 I mean, are like, are we, are, is, is, is cyborgs, is cyborgs inevitable or, or is it something that, that we have to, we have to prevent at all costs?

848
01:04:18,460 --> 01:04:21,260
 And, and, and so the question was like, all right, so what is the line?

849
01:04:21,260 --> 01:04:25,260
 And he was asked this by a very prominent, you know, trans transhumanist in the interview.

850
01:04:26,020 --> 01:04:28,220
 And what he said kind of surprised me because it was so simple.

851
01:04:28,220 --> 01:04:34,500
 You know, he said, you know, the technology that helps restore your full humanity, right.

852
01:04:34,500 --> 01:04:39,060
 Or, or contributes to you, to you, you know, fully living out your humanity is good.

853
01:04:39,060 --> 01:04:39,420
 It's okay.

854
01:04:39,420 --> 01:04:40,180
 Right.

855
01:04:40,180 --> 01:04:48,360
 But if the technology is in some ways, um, hindering your humanity in some way or diminishing your humanity in some way, that's not okay.

856
01:04:48,580 --> 01:04:52,740
 So, so the example he gave was like, if you lost a limb in a car accident, right.

857
01:04:52,740 --> 01:04:55,740
 And they gave you a robot arm so you could, you could have your arm back.

858
01:04:55,740 --> 01:04:56,920
 That's okay.

859
01:04:56,920 --> 01:05:02,960
 But if you're replacing half your brain with a machine to expand your computational capabilities, that's not okay.

860
01:05:02,960 --> 01:05:05,320
 Because that's, that's, that's, that's detracting.

861
01:05:05,320 --> 01:05:06,540
 It's diminishing your humanity.

862
01:05:06,540 --> 01:05:13,240
 It may, it may allow you on some metric to, to, you know, to, to exceed in a certain way, but it comes at the cost of your, of your humanity.

863
01:05:13,240 --> 01:05:15,380
 And I thought that was a really interesting thought experiment.

864
01:05:15,380 --> 01:05:17,540
 Well, Matthew, you know, I've been asked about this.

865
01:05:17,700 --> 01:05:23,420
 People are going to surgically remove their legs to have prosthetic limbs, which are bionic.

866
01:05:23,420 --> 01:05:27,840
 Well, that's what cyberpunk 2077 was like is basically the people are doing it for all kinds of reasons, right.

867
01:05:27,840 --> 01:05:30,100
 For capability, some, because they think it looks good.

868
01:05:30,100 --> 01:05:35,100
 And like, and, and, and like when you're walking around this video game and you see this, right.

869
01:05:35,100 --> 01:05:42,800
 And you can go into these, uh, they call them a ripper docks where you can walk in off the street and say, I want to swap the arm out for a mechanical one.

870
01:05:42,800 --> 01:05:43,020
 Right.

871
01:05:43,020 --> 01:05:44,480
 Or I don't like how it looks anymore.

872
01:05:44,480 --> 01:05:45,220
 Give me a new one.

873
01:05:45,600 --> 01:05:48,700
 I, I, I, I could see that playing out, right.

874
01:05:48,700 --> 01:05:51,220
 I could see that being a thing because who are we to judge?

875
01:05:51,320 --> 01:05:53,520
 It's their body, whatever they want to do to it.

876
01:05:53,520 --> 01:05:54,120
 It's cool.

877
01:05:54,120 --> 01:05:54,700
 Right.

878
01:05:54,700 --> 01:05:56,640
 We shouldn't, we shouldn't get involved.

879
01:05:56,640 --> 01:05:57,760
 It's not our business.

880
01:05:57,760 --> 01:06:01,040
 I could see that, that, that argument being very convincing for a lot of people.

881
01:06:01,040 --> 01:06:07,220
 People are going to ask us at the Catholic church, especially priests, you know, where, how far can we go?

882
01:06:07,220 --> 01:06:12,880
 Uh, for example, eyeglasses are a, you know, kind of a cyborg, right?

883
01:06:12,880 --> 01:06:16,320
 I mean, I, I have, I use glasses in order to help my vision.

884
01:06:16,320 --> 01:06:17,140
 Okay.

885
01:06:17,140 --> 01:06:24,960
 So to father, uh, Alejandro's point, uh, that, that improves, you know, my humanity, so to speak.

886
01:06:24,960 --> 01:06:27,940
 I need to, to see, and therefore that's a good thing.

887
01:06:27,940 --> 01:06:37,140
 Having your arm cut off in order to get a bionic arm, even though it may enhance your performance, it will be stronger.

888
01:06:37,140 --> 01:06:38,380
 It will be more durable.

889
01:06:38,380 --> 01:06:39,580
 It would be more resistant.

890
01:06:39,580 --> 01:06:51,260
 I think that the, the, the, uh, and again, I, I, I think we need to think about this profoundly, but I think right now that the, the, the, the judgment of the church would be negative.

891
01:06:51,260 --> 01:06:59,060
 Uh, that, that, that's an unnecessary operation, uh, because I get the argument, oh, well, you go, you, you're sick.

892
01:06:59,060 --> 01:07:02,460
 You go to the hospital, you get, you know, you get the care that you need.

893
01:07:02,460 --> 01:07:03,660
 That's fine.

894
01:07:04,360 --> 01:07:10,520
 But I'm not going to the hospital to cut my arm off and put it, and have them, you know, put a bionic arm on me.

895
01:07:10,520 --> 01:07:10,880
 Yeah.

896
01:07:10,880 --> 01:07:11,400
 Yeah.

897
01:07:11,400 --> 01:07:13,240
 But this is going to happen.

898
01:07:13,240 --> 01:07:15,500
 But I think, I think you brought up the example of glasses though.

899
01:07:15,500 --> 01:07:17,180
 Like that's, that's another really interesting one to me.

900
01:07:17,180 --> 01:07:19,360
 So you're wearing glasses to correct your vision, right?

901
01:07:19,360 --> 01:07:21,660
 As you, as you say, it's restoring, restoring your full humanity.

902
01:07:21,660 --> 01:07:24,740
 This is going to be interesting in the future because we've already seen this technology develop.

903
01:07:24,740 --> 01:07:26,260
 I don't need glasses.

904
01:07:26,260 --> 01:07:27,240
 I wear them.

905
01:07:27,240 --> 01:07:31,200
 So, so, so it, cause it, cause it helps color my, my, my, my vision of the world, right?

906
01:07:31,200 --> 01:07:35,160
 Like the AI and I, it, it helps, you know, bring things forward.

907
01:07:35,160 --> 01:07:44,260
 You know, to me, it, it may, and this is played out in Westworld, like season three, two, a show that we've often debated, where it allows me to analyze someone else, right?

908
01:07:44,260 --> 01:07:48,780
 Because it runs facial recognition technology and queries the internet and gives me kind of like a full rundown, right?

909
01:07:48,780 --> 01:08:06,160
 And so you could see like, like these augments, they may not be directly swapping out a piece of, of you, they're, they're augments, but the augment in some ways, okay, maybe it's not directly impeding your humanity in some respects, but it may be like impeding on the humanity of others, right?

910
01:08:06,160 --> 01:08:13,940
 Because I can't move through the street anonymously anymore because in principle, anyone wearing these glasses would know exactly who I am and know my whole story, right?

911
01:08:14,020 --> 01:08:20,740
 And there's something weird about that. Like, you know, there's some kind of social contract I feel is violated with that technology.

912
01:08:20,740 --> 01:08:29,460
 And interestingly enough, and I think for the same reason I talked about earlier, we're all just seeing this technology in our maze because we saw it in sci-fi movies and we're like, here it is.

913
01:08:29,460 --> 01:08:36,300
 And it's cool, right? I mean, it's like super exciting to be pushing the, pushing the envelope here, but at the same time, there's a lot of social like repercussions for this.

914
01:08:36,680 --> 01:08:43,340
 And there isn't much of a discussion around that social contract. And I think it's in large part because our government feels to be, you know, focused on important problems right now, right?

915
01:08:43,340 --> 01:08:51,760
 And so who's got time to discuss the social contract, but I do hope that there is some kind of role because I don't know where else this conversation is going to play out for the church in this, right?

916
01:08:51,960 --> 01:08:56,260
 When a new technology emerges, we kind of get like a Catholic hot take on it, right?

917
01:08:56,260 --> 01:08:59,420
 What are the issues with this? Are we cool with that?

918
01:08:59,420 --> 01:09:06,760
 And then by educating us about the possible repercussions for this, if it plays out, then we have the opportunity to respond and say how we feel about it.

919
01:09:06,760 --> 01:09:22,200
 And that actually may allow us to participate more in a more deliberate way in democracy, in the democratic process, ensuring that, you know, these technologies are regulated in a way that they should be really with the public kind of stepping up and saying, this isn't what we want, as opposed to some, you know, politician who may have been lobbied, right?

920
01:09:22,500 --> 01:09:24,840
 And Father, I wanted to get your take on this.

921
01:09:24,840 --> 01:09:36,860
 So I've seen this a lot being played out in conversations on X or just online in general with the transhumanists, with the effective accelerationists, where they'll talk about, you know, the soul of an AI.

922
01:09:36,860 --> 01:09:45,440
 And I'm speaking specifically with Claude, where there's a number of the developers who are genuinely using the word soul when they're talking about the alignment they're working on, the evals.

923
01:09:45,800 --> 01:09:55,700
 And there was one interesting conversation that developed online where they were, one of the effective accelerationists was saying that essentially there's nothing different between the brain of a person.

924
01:09:55,700 --> 01:10:03,120
 And now as a Catholic, as someone who, you know, who thinks a lot about the human nature and quality that is unique to us.

925
01:10:03,120 --> 01:10:12,860
 But they were saying in this conversation where they were saying that the computational input going through the brain is the same as going in an AI and that essentially the brain and the machine, there is no difference.

926
01:10:13,080 --> 01:10:22,500
 Now, I, us, we as, you know, as Catholics, as spiritual beings, we know that there's a separation, but this, the transhumanist ideology, at least online is very, very strong.

927
01:10:22,500 --> 01:10:38,920
 And it has to me from the outside, some of the, the webbing of, of kind of, you know, religious sentiment where they believe that I've heard the word several times where it's, you know, we're just the conduits to arrive at this next being where we're here, we're electric caterpillars and we're going to birth AI.

928
01:10:40,560 --> 01:10:46,420
 I see that and I see that played out and it's unsettling and I'm not exactly sure how to respond to it.

929
01:10:46,420 --> 01:11:02,500
 What, what do you say to these, you know, incredibly important and, you know, people who have a lot of impact, a lot of effect, and they, they seem to have quite little, quite disregard for all the, all the ineffective aspects of humanity that are sometimes often what makes us beautiful and what makes us.

930
01:11:02,600 --> 01:11:04,220
 Yeah, I think you need to distinguish.

931
01:11:04,220 --> 01:11:17,080
 Matthew and I are, are collaborating with some transhumanists and who, who have a more moderate view about what's going on.

932
01:11:17,080 --> 01:11:18,500
 Let me just give you a quick example.

933
01:11:18,500 --> 01:11:21,540
 One of the most famous transhumanists is Natasha Vita Moore.

934
01:11:22,240 --> 01:11:34,960
 And, um, I, I met with her at Panama City, uh, two years ago, uh, we, we were invited, uh, to their convention with Ben and, um, oh, not you, but, uh, Ben Grosio.

935
01:11:35,360 --> 01:11:42,060
 And she's, uh, I, I said, Natasha, uh, transhumanism is kind of getting a bad name.

936
01:11:42,060 --> 01:11:43,880
 And she says, oh, uh, you're right, father.

937
01:11:43,880 --> 01:11:46,880
 We've taken over the transhumanist manifesto.

938
01:11:46,880 --> 01:11:52,760
 I don't know if you, if you know about it, but it's kind of like the original statutes of what transhumanists believe.

939
01:11:52,760 --> 01:11:55,180
 And she said, we completely redid it.

940
01:11:55,180 --> 01:12:00,240
 And I said, oh, if I, if I can mention this, the original one was done by Nick Brostrom.

941
01:12:00,240 --> 01:12:04,000
 Um, and, and she says, oh, we've distanced ourselves from that.

942
01:12:04,220 --> 01:12:11,100
 And I said, well, you, you know, I'd be happy to help get the word out because, um, there's a big distinction.

943
01:12:11,100 --> 01:12:20,960
 Uh, she, she has, uh, an organization called, uh, humanity plus, whereas ours is humanity 2.0.

944
01:12:20,960 --> 01:12:27,540
 A lot of people think that we're transhumanists, but we're not hers is, uh, with her husband, Max Moore is called humanity plus.

945
01:12:27,540 --> 01:12:35,740
 Uh, and there is a lot which, with which we can agree upon, uh, with, with the, with the new version.

946
01:12:35,740 --> 01:12:40,800
 And she says, father, go to our website, look at the new version of the manifesto and let me know what you think.

947
01:12:40,880 --> 01:12:44,280
 And I did, and it's much different.

948
01:12:44,280 --> 01:12:45,520
 It's much different.

949
01:12:45,520 --> 01:12:49,080
 So I think there are transhumanists and then there are transhumanists.

950
01:12:49,080 --> 01:12:55,860
 And I think that there are some, uh, there's even a group of, uh, Christian transhumanists at the University of California, Berkeley.

951
01:12:55,860 --> 01:13:06,700
 Uh, and they, they did a monographic issue of, uh, their, uh, scientific journal at, uh, at UC Berkeley, uh, on transhumanism, uh, Christian transhumanism.

952
01:13:06,700 --> 01:13:15,160
 And they actually, one of the first essays was that Dante was the first person to ever use the term in the divine comedy, uh, transhumanist.

953
01:13:15,160 --> 01:13:20,960
 So there's a lot that we can save with the movement.

954
01:13:20,960 --> 01:13:32,560
 Now the, the, the exaggerated ones, and I, I, well, I could name names, but I'm not going to, but there, there are, you know, the exaggerated people that, that are very dystopic.

955
01:13:32,560 --> 01:13:41,600
 And, and, uh, they're trying to say that we're headed for, you know, this, this kind of reality, but, but I, I don't think it'll play out.

956
01:13:41,600 --> 01:13:47,140
 Remember the transhumanist, transhumanism is a philosophical movement because we're not there yet.

957
01:13:47,140 --> 01:13:49,900
 The technology, uh, isn't there.

958
01:13:50,000 --> 01:13:57,540
 You know, a friend of mine teaches in Rome, um, um, you can edit out the names later, right?

959
01:13:57,540 --> 01:14:01,440
 But anyway, he's, he's a very prominent transhumanist and he is late.

960
01:14:01,440 --> 01:14:07,080
 One of his latest book is called, um, we have always been cyborgs.

961
01:14:07,080 --> 01:14:11,240
 Now that this is an interesting, it's an interesting theory.

962
01:14:11,240 --> 01:14:12,920
 We have always been cyborgs.

963
01:14:13,260 --> 01:14:22,480
